---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  keywords={keywords}
  canonical={canonical}
  schema={combinedSchema}
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-sage/20 to-ivory py-16 md:py-20 -mx-4 px-4 mb-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-granite mb-6">
        National Gym Grading Study
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">
        Comprehensive Analysis of Climbing Grade Variability Across U.S. Indoor Facilities
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-6 mt-8 text-lg">
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <span class="text-4xl font-bold text-sage">{totalGyms}</span>
          <span class="text-gray-600">Gyms Analyzed</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <span class="text-4xl font-bold text-sage">{regions}</span>
          <span class="text-gray-600">U.S. Regions</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <span class="text-4xl font-bold text-sage">{states}</span>
          <span class="text-gray-600">States Covered</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
    <!-- Introduction -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-4">Overview</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-700">
        <p>
          Climbing gym grades are notoriously inconsistent. A V4 in one gym might feel like a V2 or V6 in another. For traveling climbers and those training across multiple facilities, this variability makes it difficult to track progress, identify weaknesses, and structure effective training programs.
        </p>
        <p>
          This study analyzes grade ranges, setting philosophies, and wall styles across 40 climbing gyms in the United States to quantify these differences and help climbers understand how grading varies by region, gym type, and wall style.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Methodology -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-4">Methodology</h2>
      <div class="prose max-w-none text-gray-700">
        <p>
          This research analyzed 40 indoor climbing facilities across the West Coast, South, Midwest, and Northeast regions of the United States. Data was collected from publicly available sources including gym websites, online reviews, and climber feedback.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Data Sources:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Official gym websites (grade ranges, wall specifications)</li>
          <li>Instagram and social media (wall angles, setting styles, climber feedback)</li>
          <li>Online climbing forums and review platforms (Mountain Project, Reddit, Google Reviews)</li>
          <li>Direct climber testimonials and community consensus</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Variables Examined:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Grade ranges:</strong> Maximum and minimum grades offered for bouldering and rope climbing</li>
          <li><strong>Wall styles:</strong> Dominant wall features (steep overhangs, slabs, volumes, vertical walls)</li>
          <li><strong>Setting philosophy:</strong> Competition-style vs. commercial vs. training-focused</li>
          <li><strong>Grading assessment:</strong> Classified as Very Soft, Soft, Medium, Hard, or Very Hard based on climber consensus and comparison to outdoor equivalents</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Classification Methodology:</strong></p>
        <p>
          Each gym was assigned a grading classification based on multiple factors including setter style, business model (commercial vs. training-focused), wall angles, and aggregated climber feedback patterns. Grading classifications were determined through cross-referencing multiple data sources to establish consensus on how each facility's grades compare to outdoor climbing standards and other gyms.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Study Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>This is a representative snapshot of 40 facilities, not a comprehensive census of all U.S. climbing gyms</li>
          <li>Grade assessments reflect general patterns and may not apply to every route set at a given gym</li>
          <li>Setting styles and grading philosophies can change over time as staff and ownership evolve</li>
          <li>Individual climber experience varies based on personal strengths, weaknesses, and training background</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Key Findings -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-4">Key Findings</h2>
