        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-sage/10 to-ivory p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-sage">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-2">Regional Patterns</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            The Northeast skewed harder overall, while the South trended softer. The West Coast showed the widest variance, with gyms ranging from very soft to very hard. The Midwest demonstrated the most consistency.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-sage/10 to-ivory p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-sage">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-2">Wall Style Correlation</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            Wall style proved to be the strongest predictor of grading philosophy. Steep, overhang-dominated gyms consistently graded harder, while slab and vertical-heavy facilities skewed softer.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-sage/10 to-ivory p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-sage">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-2">Gym Type Impact</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            Commercial chains grade approximately one full V-grade softer than training-focused facilities. This reflects different business models and target audiences rather than inconsistency.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-sage/10 to-ivory p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-sage">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-2">Grade Variance Range</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            A solid V4 climber could reasonably expect to climb V2-V6 across different gyms, depending on wall angle, hold style, and setting philosophy—a significant disruption to training progressions.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

